  "prompt": "Why are speedometers inaccurate?",
  "response": "Speedometers can be inaccurate for several reasons:\n\n1. Tire size variations\n- Different tire sizes and wear can affect the actual speed reading\n- New tires are slightly larger than worn tires, which changes wheel rotation\n\n2. Manufacturing tolerances\n- Mechanical and electronic speedometers have small built-in measurement errors\n- Components are not perfectly precise\n\n3. Mechanical design limitations\n- Older mechanical speedometers use cables and gears that can stretch or wear\n- This leads to gradual inaccuracy over time\n\n4. Electronic sensor issues\n- Sensors can become less precise with age\n- Calibration can drift over time\n\n5. Temperature and environmental factors\n- Extreme temperatures can affect speedometer components\n- Vibration and mechanical stress can impact accuracy\n\n6. Intentional over-reporting\n- Some manufacturers slightly overstate speed to appear conservative\n- Helps prevent potential legal issues related to precise speed measurement\n\n7. Aftermarket modifications\n- Changing wheel size or suspension can alter speedometer readings\n- Requires recalibration to maintain accuracy\n\nMost modern digital speedometers are more accurate than older mechanical versions, but some degree of inaccuracy is still common.",
